          "Living in Cleveland creates some unique check engine light situations that drivers in other regions do not deal with. First, cold-weather misfires. When temperatures drop below 20 degrees — which happens frequently from December through February — worn spark plugs and weak ignition coils that work fine in warm weather cannot generate enough spark to ignite cold, dense air-fuel mixtures. If your check engine light comes on during the first cold snap of winter, spark plugs and coils are the first suspects. Second, EVAP codes from temperature swings. Cleveland's 100-plus degree annual temperature range causes fuel vapors to expand and contract dramatically, stressing EVAP system components. We see a spike in EVAP-related check engine lights during spring and fall when daytime and nighttime temperatures diverge by 30 or 40 degrees. Third, road salt damage to wiring harnesses. Salt spray from Cleveland's aggressively salted roads corrodes electrical connectors and sensor wiring. A corroded O2 sensor connector mimics a failed O2 sensor, and a corroded wiring harness on a crankshaft position sensor will throw random misfire codes. We always inspect wiring connectors before condemning sensors, because a $15 connector cleaning solves a problem that might otherwise lead to a $300 sensor replacement. Fourth, pothole-induced sensor damage. A hard pothole impact can jar loose electrical connectors or crack sensor housings. If your check engine light comes on right after hitting a big pothole, mechanical damage to sensors or connectors is the likely cause.",
