        heading: "Quick Diagnosis: What Happens When You Turn the Key?",
        content:
          "When your car will not start, the sound it makes — or does not make — is the single biggest diagnostic clue. Pay attention to exactly what happens when you turn the key or press the start button, because this tells you which system has failed. If you hear nothing at all — no clicks, no sounds, dashboard lights are dim or off — the most likely cause is a dead battery or a loose or corroded battery connection. If you hear a rapid clicking sound, like a machine gun of clicks, the battery has some charge but not enough to turn the starter motor. This usually means the battery is weak or dying. If you hear a single loud click followed by nothing, the starter solenoid is engaging but the starter motor is not spinning. This typically means the starter motor has failed. If the engine cranks normally — that familiar ruh-ruh-ruh-ruh sound — but will not fire and run, the problem is not the battery or starter. Instead, the engine is not getting fuel, spark, or compression. This is a separate category of problems including bad fuel pumps, crank sensors, or ignition issues. In Cleveland winters, the most common no-start cause by far is battery failure. Cold temperatures reduce battery capacity by 30 to 50 percent, and a battery that started your car fine in September may not have enough power on a 5-degree January morning. Our shop sees a surge of battery replacements every year starting in late November.",
