        heading: "Undercoating and Rust Prevention Treatments",
        content:
          "The most effective defense against road salt is undercoating — a protective coating applied to the entire undercarriage of the vehicle. There are three main types. Oil-based undercoating, like Krown or Fluid Film, is a creeping oil that penetrates into crevices, displaces moisture, and leaves a self-healing film that provides excellent corrosion protection. It needs to be reapplied annually, typically in the fall before salt season, and costs $100 to $200 per application. This is the best value option for most Cleveland drivers. Rubberized undercoating is a thicker, permanent coating that creates a physical barrier against salt and moisture. The downside is that if moisture gets behind the coating through a chip or crack, it traps the moisture against the metal and can actually accelerate corrosion in that spot. Rubberized undercoating works best on new or nearly-new vehicles where the undercarriage is still clean and rust-free. Cost is $200 to $500 for professional application. Wax-based undercoating like NH Oil is a middle ground — it provides good penetration and protection, dries to a more durable film than oil-based products, and lasts about a year. For Cleveland vehicles, we recommend an annual oil-based or wax-based treatment applied in October. If your vehicle is new, start immediately — it is much easier and cheaper to prevent rust than to stop it once it has started.",
