          "The fundamental principle of winter driving is that every input to the vehicle — steering, braking, and acceleration — must be gentler than normal because you have less traction available. Smooth and gradual is the mantra. When accelerating from a stop on snow or ice, press the gas gently and progressively. If your wheels start to spin, ease off the gas until they grip, then gradually reapply. Many modern vehicles have traction control that does this automatically, but the system works better when you work with it rather than mashing the gas and letting electronics sort it out. When braking, apply firm steady pressure and let the ABS do its job. If you feel the ABS pulsing through the pedal, that is normal — it means the system is preventing wheel lock-up. Do not pump ABS brakes like you would with older non-ABS systems. Increase your following distance to at least six seconds behind the vehicle in front of you. At 35 mph on packed snow, your stopping distance is roughly three times what it is on dry pavement. On ice, it can be eight to ten times longer. When turning, slow down before the turn, not during it. Braking in a turn on snow or ice is the number one cause of spinouts. Approach the turn at a speed that does not require braking through the curve, turn the wheel smoothly, and gently accelerate out of the turn. On hills, maintain steady momentum going uphill without stopping if possible, and use low gear or engine braking going downhill rather than riding the brakes. If your vehicle has all-wheel drive or four-wheel drive, understand that these systems help you accelerate but do not help you stop or turn. AWD vehicles crash into guardrails at the same rate as front-wheel-drive vehicles on ice because the physics of stopping are identical.",
